1. What is a String?

A String is a sequence of characters.
In Java, a String is an object, not a primitive data type.

Example:

String name = "Rakheeb";

2. How Strings are Stored
In Java, Strings are stored in a special memory area called the String Constant Pool (SCP).

Important points:
When you create a string using " " (double quotes), it goes to SCP.
Java stores only one copy of each literal.
If two strings have the same literal, they share the same memory location.

Example:

String s1 = "Hello";
String s2 = "Hello";  // same reference as s1

3. String is Immutable

Strings cannot be changed after creation.
Whenever you modify a string, Java creates a new object.

Example:

String s = "Hi";
s = s + " John";   // creates a new object


Reason for immutability:

Security
Thread safety
String pool efficiency

4. Ways to Create a String
Method 1: Using string literal
String s = "Hello";

Method 2: Using new keyword
String s = new String("Hello");

Difference:

Literal goes to String Pool
new keyword creates a new object in heap memory

5. Important String Methods (Beginner Level)
Length of string
s.length();

Get character at index
s.charAt(2);

Check equality
s1.equals(s2);

Check equality ignoring case
s1.equalsIgnoreCase(s2);

Convert to uppercase
s.toUpperCase();

Convert to lowercase
s.toLowerCase();

Check if empty
s.isEmpty();

6. Searching in Strings
Find first index of character
s.indexOf('a');

Find last index
s.lastIndexOf('a');

Check if substring exists
s.contains("abc");

7. Substrings
Method:
s.substring(startIndex);
s.substring(startIndex, endIndex);


Example:

String s = "Hello";
String part = s.substring(1, 4);   // "ell"

8. String Comparison: equals vs ==
equals()

Compares value.

==

Compares memory address (reference).

Example:

String a = "Hi";
String b = "Hi";
System.out.println(a == b);       // true (same SCP reference)
System.out.println(a.equals(b));  // true


But:

String x = new String("Hi");
String y = new String("Hi");
System.out.println(x == y);       // false
System.out.println(x.equals(y));  // true

9. StringBuilder and StringBuffer (Medium Level)

Because Strings are immutable, repeated modifications are slow.
To fix this, Java provides:

StringBuilder (Not thread-safe, faster)
StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder("Hello");
sb.append(" World");

StringBuffer (Thread-safe, slower)
StringBuffer sb = new StringBuffer("Hello");
sb.append(" World");


Use StringBuilder for competitive coding and DSA problems.

10. Important StringBuilder Methods
append()
insert()
delete()
reverse()
length()
charAt()
setCharAt()


Example:

StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder("abcd");
sb.reverse();    // dcba

11. Splitting Strings
s.split(" ");
Example:

String s = "Java is fun";
String[] arr = s.split(" ");   // ["Java", "is", "fun"]

12. Converting String to char array
char[] ch = s.toCharArray();

13. String + Time Complexity (Important for Interviews)

Access char at index: O(1)
equals(): O(n)
substring(): O(n)
concat (+ operator): O(n)
append() in StringBuilder: O(1) amortized

